<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-419-834  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 419 834.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>High Technology Business  July-August 1989 v9 n7 p14(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Whole-Earth technology. (technology transfers; includes relatedarticle on Fairchild Semiconductor's agreement with Hungarian firmTungsram Co.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Reichert, William; Sello, Harry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>US high-technology firms must learn to buy and sell technology inthe world market to stay competitive with aggressive firms inEurope, Japan and other Pacific Rim countries.andP;  Technologytransfer may take several forms, including license agreements,cooperative development or research programs, joint ventures,equity investment, corporate mergers or offshore subsidiaries.andO;US-foreign company technology transfers have a 70 percent failurerate, with international joint ventures ranking as particularlyrisky, according to a study by McKinsey andamp; Co and Coopers andamp;Lybrand.andP;  Several steps are recommended to assure US firms'success.andP;  Choose a partner carefully.andP;  Make a long-termcommitment.andP;  Set clearly defined market-oriented objectives.andP;  Letthe venture fail if it does not meet the goals.andP;  Keep control ofthe firm's technology.andP;  An experienced attorney should be involvedin the project from the initial-planning stage.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Technology transferHigh technologyStrategic PlanningAnalysisMarketingIntellectual propertyResearch and DevelopmentCooperative Agreement.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Tech transfer checklist. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>